ed form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Sulzbach","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Horst.","German and Jewish (western Ashkenazic): habitational name from any of the many places called Sulzbach."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gebhard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>geb</i>, <i>gib</i> ‘gift’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. St Gebhard was a 10th-century bishop of Constance who founded the abbey of Petershausen."],"variants":[{"name":"Gebbert","meanings":["from <i>geb</i>, <i>gib</i> ‘gift’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. St Gebhard was a 10th-century bishop of Constance who founded the abbey of Petershausen."]}]},{"name":"II.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gebhard II. von Sulzbach was born about 1055, in Amberg, Bavaria, Germany, his father, Gebhard I. von Sulzbach-Schwaben, was 22 and his mother, Adelheid von Sulzbach-Nordgau, was 27. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Irmgard von Rott. He died in 1085, in Sulzbach, Bavaria, Germany, at the age of 31, and was buried in Kastl, Amberg-Sulzbach, Bavaria, Germany."},"et":{"um 1055–1085":"umbes 1055–1085","1055–1085":"1055–1085","1064–1101":"1064–1101","1076–Female":"1076–Surnud","1080–1125":"1080–1125","1035–1071":"1035–1071","1030–1091":"1030–1091","1091":"1091","1080":"1080","105